-EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> ). Each player would be free to create and to be anything they wanted to be. What a fantastic way to express yourself and way to meet and hang out with friends in a totally unique environment.<br><br>And this was true to some extent:  I have grouped with retired seniors in Florida to 12 year-old japanese kids. For a time it was a excellent way to spend time with my sister and brother in law who lived 3000 miles away. I got several of my RL friends involved in the game and we had a great group going for a while. I have met some wonderful and witty people with personalities that lit up the sky.<br><br>But on the whole, does the game live up to it's incredible promise? How much of your time do you spend socializing and how much mindlessly whacking on mobs, or sitting in EC watching auctions, or just waiting around medding, etc. How many people do you really try to meet? When it comes down to it I don't think that the vast majority of people on lanys are really that social and interested in meeting you.<br><br>In short, most of the game experience ends up being mindless crap. Maybe you could say the same thing about real life too, but at least it is mindless crap that isn't confined to a 17 inch monitor.<br><br>So all i can say about EQ in the final analysis is that it is a great way to kill time. But remember what Henry David Thoreau said:  &quot;As if you could kill time without injuring eternity.&quot;  <br><br>Some of you need to quit. You know who you are. So do it. You can, trust me. To the others who play the game with creativity, wit, and fire, I salute you in your adventures.<br><br>/wave<br>Tom<br><br>otherwise known as:<br><br>Tubbs the Troll, 45 SK<br>Lugubrious, 21 troll shaman<br>Eldepryl, 22 gnome necromancer<br>Weebl, 20 gnome warrior<br>Heatmoon, 26 human monk<br>Kenoma, 21 DEF warrior<br>Buspar,